{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 22:49:02.751358", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos lab\\nDate: now\\n\\n1) Executive summary\\n- The network control plane (FRR BGP) appears healthy: BGP sessions between leaves/spines/super‑spine are established and the static /24 host prefixes are present in the routing tables.\\n- There is an isolated data‑plane anomaly affecting a single host: pc_0_1 is experiencing significant packet loss/corruption on its access interface (eth0). This is causing intermittent reachability from that host to other hosts (ICMP loss up to 75% observed).\\n- Root cause (high confidence): a netem traffic control rule on pc_0_1\\'s eth0 is configured to corrupt traffic (tc qdisc shows \"corrupt 60%\"), producing high packet loss/corruption. Network devices (leaf_router_0_1 and upstream routers) are not exhibiting BGP or routing failures that would explain the observed host‑level loss.\\n\\n2) Symptoms observed\\n- In the automated reachability sweep, pc_0_1 had unknown/failed test results while other hosts reached each other normally.\\n- Active tests from pc_0_1:\\n  - Ping to 10.3.2.2: 4 transmitted, 1 received → 75% packet loss (rtt ~5.9 ms for the single reply).\\n  - Ping to its gateway 10.0.1.1: 4 transmitted, 3 received → 25% packet loss.\\n- Interface counters on pc_0_1 show few packets (small RX/TX counts) but no kernel-level errors (no RX/TX errors in ifconfig).\\n- tc (traffic control) on pc_0_1 eth0 shows a netem qdisc with \"corrupt 60%\".\\n\\n3) Evidence collected (key outputs)\\n- Reachability summary: all other hosts reached each other successfully; only pc_0_1 had issues in the initial sweep.\\n- Ping from pc_0_1 → 10.3.2.2:\\n  - 4 packets sent, 1 received, 75% loss.\\n- Ping from pc_0_1 → 10.0.1.1:\\n  - 4 packets sent, 3 received, 25% loss.\\n- ip -s link show eth0 on pc_0_1:\\n  - RX: 572 bytes, 7 packets; TX: 1386 bytes, 17 packets; no RX/TX errors.\\n- tc qdisc output on pc_0_1:\\n  - qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\\n  - Sent 1428 bytes 18 pkt ...\\n- leaf_router_0_1:\\n  - eth8 is 10.0.1.1/24 and shows traffic (RX packets 18, TX 8).\\n  - BGP configuration and routes present: 10.0.1.0/24 is directly connected on the leaf and advertised/seen in BGP.\\n- FRR BGP summaries (leafs, spines, super‑spine): peers are up; prefixes for /24 host subnets are present across routers.\\n\\n4) Localization (faulty device / interface)\\n- Fault localized to host pc_0_1, interface eth0.\\n  - Evidence: host‑local tc netem corrupt 60% and loss observed when pinging gateway as well as remote hosts. Upstream leaf (leaf_router_0_1 eth8 — 10.0.1.1) is UP and participating in BGP; routing entries for 10.0.1.0/24 are present.\\n- No indication of BGP or routing instability on leaf_router_0_1 or on spines/super‑spine. Control plane appears normal.\\n\\n5) Root cause analysis\\n- The immediate technical cause of the packet loss is intentional or configured packet corruption on pc_0_1\\'s eth0 (netem qdisc configured with corrupt 60%). netem corruption causes packets to be marked/altered such that they are effectively lost from an application/ICMP perspective or trigger retransmits.\\n- Since the router and upstream devices show normal BGP adjacencies and routing, this is not a forwarding/routing propagation issue; it is a host-level impairment.\\n- Possible origins (for operator awareness only, not remediation): netem could have been configured intentionally for testing/simulation or accidentally by a script or experiment on the host. Hardware NIC errors are unlikely given absence of RX/TX error counters and the explicit tc output showing corruption.\\n\\n6) Impact\\n- pc_0_1 experiences severe packet corruption/loss, resulting in intermittent or poor connectivity to other hosts and the rest of the network. Other hosts and routers are unaffected.\\n- BGP advertisements for 10.0.1.0/24 remain present in the fabric (leaf advertises the network), so traffic from other hosts toward the 10.0.1.0/24 prefix will be forwarded toward the leaf; packets arriving at pc_0_1 will be subject to the corruption/loss locally.\\n\\n7) Confidence and next diagnostic suggestions\\n- Confidence: high that the problem is host‑local and caused by the configured netem corruption on pc_0_1 eth0 (direct evidence from tc).\\n- Useful follow-up (diagnostic-only) checks if you want further confirmation:\\n  - Inspect full tc qdisc show output and tc filter rules on pc_0_1 to see exact netem parameters.\\n  - Check any recent host scripts/cronjobs or manual commands that could have applied netem.\\n  - Temporarily run tcpdump on pc_0_1 and on leaf_router_0_1 eth8 to observe packet loss/corruption patterns at link level (to confirm packets arriving at leaf but being corrupted at host).\\n  - Confirm other hosts\\' behaviour toward 10.0.1.2 (pc_0_1) to determine whether corruption affects inbound or outbound more.\\n\\n8) Conclusion\\n- Control plane (BGP) and routing are healthy across the Clos fabric. The only anomaly is a host‑level netem corruption rule on pc_0_1 causing significant packet loss/corruption on eth0. The problem is localized to that host interface and is not due to BGP/routing failures or upstream router faults.\\n\\nIf you want, I can (only upon request) gather the full tc qdisc/filter configuration on pc_0_1 and capture packet traces to further document the corruption behavior., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='77bfe71e-6e3b-42b6-9a57-c70d663de68a'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
